46,-0.06510617,-0.02619087,-0.03445408,-0.03286663,-0.08535579,0.01454259,-0.01243704,0.03914666,0.02296274,0.01338504,0.01575832,0.05979411,-0.03256831,-0.01804268,0.05033649,-0.0167985,-0.04763909,0.04382902,-0.00858827,0.01226216,-0.00446583,0.04624821,-0.04129336,0.0022318,0.06399316,-0.00688819,0.01402855,-0.02311869,0.05928838,0.00957239,-0.04288602,0.03599583,0.0258565,0.12018353,-0.04120545,0.04778432,0.02635541,-0.00182398,-0.03158364,0.01250008,-0.00739572,-0.00618516,0.02071185,-0.03172517,0.04700742,-0.05212419,-0.01594228,0.00873751,0.03750401,0.07807287,-0.03205032,0.00242836,-0.06548923,-0.01149939,0.00841424,0.01585182,-0.00090671,-0.05309557,-0.04310633,-0.00409206,-0.0039931,0.00197768,0.02210771,0.03430181,0.02055531,-0.03997952,-0.01957112,-0.04392964,-0.04791685,0.03418557,-0.03853457,0.01780511,-0.01252591,0.07106525,0.00496905,-0.03507752,-0.0197198,0.00517898,0.02025287,-0.01504242,-0.02742282,0.00980345,0.0021056,-0.01238798,-0.01879353,-0.04128568,-0.04533703,0.00947657,0.06706553,0.06896007,0.00819997,-0.00184112,-0.00437857,0.0378788,-0.02608888,0.04038557,-0.0010605,-0.00453283,0.02308033,0.08970682,-0.06593879,0.02271087,-0.01924654,-0.00595096,0.05949578,0.01499654,-0.02093546,-0.04615802,-0.00187363,0.01483797,-0.01546093,0.00849835,-0.03997607,0.00000118,0.0265215,-0.00031432,-0.04189361,0.00066481,0.05483248,-0.01812682,-0.01553234,-0.03482411,0.03778505],"last_embed":{"hash":"a6ca706c3209c51436070956781579a547b7eff4f4f4248665275fbe00a31bbe","tokens":1168}}},"text":null,"length":0,"last_read":{"hash":"a6ca706c3209c51436070956781579a547b7eff4f4f4248665275fbe00a31bbe","at":1742533452264},"key":"DDD 的实战（第十章）.md#Side-Effect-Free Functions","lines":[40,58],"size":3268,"outlinks":[{"title":"In standard English, the term side effect implies an unintended consequence, but in computer science, it means any effect on the state of the system.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":3},{"title":"As soon as this arbitrarily deep nesting is involved, it becomes very hard to anticipate all the consequences of invoking an operation.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":5},{"title":"The use of the term side effect underlines the inevitability of that interaction.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":7},{"title":"The usefulness of any abstraction of interfaces is limited if the developers are forced to pierce the veil.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":10},{"title":"Obviously, you can’t avoid commands in most software systems, but the problem can be mitigated in two ways.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":12},{"title":"But by definition, this segregation of side effects into simple command methods only applies to ENTITIES.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":13},{"title":"The side effectoften can be completely eliminated by deriving a VALUE OBJECT instead of changing existing state, or by moving the entire responsibility into a VALUE OBJECT.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":15},{"title":"Strictly segregate commands (methods that result in modifications to observable state) into very simple operations that do not return domain information. Further control side effects by moving complex logic into VALUE OBJECTS when a concept fitting the responsibility presents itself.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":17}],"class_name":"SmartBlock"},
