89,0.01683456,-0.05996424,-0.00843004,-0.05586629,-0.03033864,-0.02817963,0.03192878,0.07183336,0.00384847,-0.0190098,-0.06234515,-0.01991903,-0.01030675,0.02966414,-0.02873007,-0.02451009,-0.05212364,0.00270994,0.0006412,0.02031195,0.0340758,0.05117284,0.03704387,-0.03669031,-0.01900826,0.0012254,-0.05158248,0.01336826,0.0100864,0.01883467,0.03007416,0.0524489,0.00567823,-0.00144375,-0.0482837,0.00192519,0.02604569,-0.03149287,-0.01524402,0.04407988,-0.01666342,-0.02563542,-0.02098933,-0.07205767,-0.0474916,0.01044832,0.03333171,0.06460242,-0.00360168,0.01535598,-0.0099897,0.05932302,-0.02475695,0.03239389,-0.01101721,-0.02015756,0.021073,0.09077395,-0.07806198,-0.01064632,0.01599251,-0.01877094,0.07255881,-0.0015213,0.00162403,-0.06452409,0.05734633,0.00608851,0.00225108,-0.03009334,-0.03385567,0.00000121,-0.02840095,0.02489456,-0.05374484,0.01584993,0.01532776,-0.01433371,-0.02682064,-0.06596834,0.0340592],"last_embed":{"hash":"c63bf2e5521116609384c3abdee1adb01651f00d98de46ab62758aa33fc54d82","tokens":727}}},"text":null,"length":0,"last_read":{"hash":"c63bf2e5521116609384c3abdee1adb01651f00d98de46ab62758aa33fc54d82","at":1742533807291},"key":"DDD 的实战（第十章）.md#Intention-revealing interfaces","lines":[28,39],"size":2255,"outlinks":[{"title":"We are always fighting cognitive overload: If the client developer’s mind is flooded with detail about how a component does its job, his mind isn’t clear to work out the intricacies of the client design.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":3},{"title":"To obtain the value of explicitly modeling a concept in the form of a class or method, we must give these program elements names that reflect those concepts. The names of classes and methods are great opportunities for improving communication between developers, and for improving the abstraction of the system.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":6},{"title":"In the public interfaces of the domain: state relationships and rules, but not how they are enforced; describe events and actions, but not how they are carried out; formulate the equation but not the numerical method to solve it. Pose the question, but don’t present the means by which the answer shall be found.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":9},{"title":"Entire subdomains can be carved off into separate modules and encapsulated behind INTENTION-REVEALINGINTERFACES. Using such whittling to focus a project and manage the complexity of a large system will be discussed more in Chapter 15, “Distillation,” with COHESIVE MECHANISMS and GENERIC SUBDOMAINS.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":11}],"class_name":"SmartBlock"},
