-0.0492314,-0.00572787,-0.05603675,0.00810705,-0.00391103,-0.01298024,0.08950864,-0.04826345,-0.00617085,-0.03521801,-0.02802635,-0.00044778,0.04448876,-0.01095006,-0.05431503,-0.03549951,-0.03477326,0.00768311,-0.0173861,-0.00209171,0.06834553,0.01198776,-0.04598187,0.04595516,-0.03529799,-0.03135826,0.01734609,-0.00889885,0.01537599,0.03558937,0.03650587,0.00233999,-0.03918463,-0.00718312,0.04573967,0.05544691,-0.05088476,-0.04446384,-0.00150508,-0.03068794,0.00254305,-0.01892884,-0.06725478,-0.06276447,-0.00388293,0.06346429,0.0583645,-0.03626145,0.00258076,-0.01355224,0.05381203,-0.00378819,0.06723475,-0.01374969,-0.00233213,0.00055116,0.05415564,-0.06495923,0.00141937,0.01063971,-0.03760239,0.03360929,-0.00133509,-0.03110134,-0.10845964,0.06366961,-0.00533778,-0.04758146,-0.01714852,-0.04000187,0.00000116,0.00627271,-0.02436546,-0.053351,-0.01468901,0.0151963,-0.00667695,0.01159228,-0.0439284,0.01365053],"last_embed":{"hash":"1b0fa9adb2f031418264d0a19b26a094c41649b33442aee2ba13fb40c419b29c","tokens":1111}}},"text":null,"length":0,"last_read":{"hash":"1b0fa9adb2f031418264d0a19b26a094c41649b33442aee2ba13fb40c419b29c","at":1742533810460},"key":"DDD 的实战（第十章）.md#Closure of Operation#{1}","lines":[152,171],"size":3104,"outlinks":[{"title":"Stripping interfaces down to deal with nothing but primitives can impoverish them.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":1},{"title":"Mathematicians are fanatical about not introducing extraneous concepts, and theproperty of closure provides them a way of defining an operation without involving any other concepts.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":4},{"title":"The property of closure tremendously simplifies the interpretation of an operation, and it is easyto think about chaining together or combining closed operations.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":7},{"title":"If the implementer has state that is used in the computation, then the implementer is effectively an argument of the operation, so the argument(s) and return value should be of the same type as the implementer.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":9},{"title":"you can’t just conjure up a new one to answer a question","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":14},{"title":"The argument matches the implementer, but the return type is different, or thereturn type matches the receiver and the argument is different. These operations are not closed, but they dogive some of the advantages of CLOSURE. When the extra type is a primitive or basic library class, it frees themind almost as much as CLOSURE.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":16},{"title":"The usefulness of a MODEL-DRIVEN DESIGN is sensitive to the quality of the detailed design and implementation decisions, and it only takes a few confused developers to derail a project from the goal.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":18}],"class_name":"SmartBlock"},
